{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01B9avCcnCR4mnVjeHSNiaSN","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. The TLS cert has SANs for:\n- DNS:localhost\n- DNS:*.elasticsearch.svc\n- DNS:*.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local\n\nThis means the service `es-http.elasticsearch.svc` and `es-http.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` will be valid. Also wildcard `*.elasticsearch.svc` covers any service in the namespace.\n\nNow I need to deploy:\n1. A ConfigMap with elasticsearch.yml config\n2. A headless Service for transport (es-transport) for inter-node communication\n3. An es-http Service for HTTPS on port 9200\n4. A StatefulSet with 3 replicas\n\nFor Elasticsearch 8.x TLS, I'll use the es-http-tls secret for both HTTP and transport layer encryption since the certificate SANs cover the pod hostnames through the wildcard patterns.\n\nThe issue is that pod FQDNs like `es-0.es-transport.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` don't match the wildcard `*.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` (it only covers one subdomain level). I could either disable transport hostname verification, generate transport certificates at pod startup, or use the existing cert with relaxed verification settings. The simplest approach is to use the same TLS cert for both layers but configure transport verification to check the certificate validity without strict hostname matching.\n\nFor a basic 3-node cluster, I'll enable security by default and configure the HTTP layer with the existing TLS secret, then set transport TLS to use certificate verification mode which validates the cert without hostname checking—acceptable for same-cluster communication.\n\nConfiguring elasticsearch.yml... Writing Elasticsearch config...\n\nI need to think through the node naming and discovery setup for the StatefulSet. Each pod will get a stable hostname like `es-0`, `es-1`, `es-2`, and I should use a headless service called `es-transport` to enable pod-to-pod communication via DNS names like `es-0.es-transport.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`. The discovery configuration needs to reference this headless service so the nodes can find each other during cluster formation.\n\nFor the Java heap size, I'll set it to 512MB for a test cluster, and I need to configure resource requests and limits. I also need to plan out the persistent volume claims for data storage.\n\nLooking at the TLS certificate SANs, the pod addresses won't match the certificate's DNS names, so I'll need to set `verification_mode: certificate` for transport layer security. For Elasticsearch 8 with security enabled, I need to set the elastic user password via the `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` environment variable during initialization.\n\nWriting the complete manifest... Writing Kubernetes config... Writing Kubernetes manifest...\n\nI'm noticing an issue with how the node name is being set in the Elasticsearch configuration—it's using a variable reference that might not resolve properly in this context. I should add a PodDisruptionBudget for better availability. The TLS setup should work fine since I'm using certificate verification mode without hostname checking, and the secret format is already PEM which Elasticsearch expects. Now I'll put together the complete manifest and deploy it.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":315,"cache_read_input_tokens":29225,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":315},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f7cc2bc1-d1ae-4b8c-ae09-e1ca7d9cdcd8","uuid":"8c691480-1251-4c99-b857-06c46e16d25e","request_id":"req_011CcfCgLYxZ7Y6bXj9AKhCf"}
