{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01BXXZ8ozRveWnYiAJTjNKz2","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The DNS resolution is failing for the pod hostnames. This is strange. The headless service is `es-transport`, but the pods can't resolve either the service itself or pod-specific hostnames.\n\nWait, for StatefulSet pod DNS to work, the headless service needs to be created BEFORE the pods. Let me check if the service was created correctly.\n\nActually, I deleted the original StatefulSet and only deleted/recreated the StatefulSet - the services were already created. But let me check if the headless service is correctly set up.\n\nAlso, the issue might be that `getent` is failing, not DNS. \n\nThere could be a timing issue where pods start in parallel but DNS entries for StatefulSet pods only appear once they get an IP assigned. If all three pods start simultaneously, none have DNS entries initially, and CoreDNS might be caching the \"no such host\" response. But more likely, the pod subdomain isn't configured correctly—for DNS names like `es-0.es-transport.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` to work, the service and StatefulSet need to be properly linked via the `serviceName` field.\n\nThe StatefulSet does have `serviceName: es-transport` and the headless service exists with matching selectors, so the DNS names should resolve. But when even `getent hosts es-transport.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` fails, it points to either a service misconfiguration, CoreDNS issues, or the service not actually existing. I should verify the service setup.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":328,"cache_read_input_tokens":45920,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":328},"output_tokens":23,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management