{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_0169DZ7Uosh3cef6Vk18afui","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The nodes can reach each other via IP, but DNS hostname resolution is failing. So the issue is CoreDNS not resolving the pod hostnames. This happens because the pods are NOT Ready (0/1), so CoreDNS won't add their A records to the headless service DNS.\n\nWait - actually for StatefulSet headless services, even pods that are not Ready should get DNS entries. Let me check the Kubernetes documentation...\n\nActually, this is a known behavior: by default, Kubernetes only publishes DNS A records for pods that are Ready. For headless services, the DNS records for individual pods (`pod-name.service.namespace`) ARE created even if not Ready, because StatefulSet pods have a stable identity and hostname.\nBut I'm second-guessing myself here. The service DNS query returned nothing, meaning no ready pods exist for that service. And querying the individual pod DNS also returned nothing, which shouldn't happen if StatefulSet pods get DNS entries regardless of readiness state.\n\nLooking at the Kubernetes documentation more carefully, I realize that `publishNotReadyAddresses` controls whether DNS records are published for pods that aren't Ready yet. It defaults to false, so pod DNS won't resolve unless the pod passes its readiness checks. That's the issue—Elasticsearch needs to discover other nodes in the cluster even before they're fully ready, so I need to enable `publishNotReadyAddresses: true` on the headless service. Let me update the service configuration with that setting.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":576,"cache_read_input_tokens":47226,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":576},"output_tokens":18,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnos